  "prompt": "So, can a sentence begin with the word \"so\"?",
  "response": "Yes, a sentence can begin with the word \"so.\" This usage has become increasingly common in both informal and formal writing and speech. While some traditional grammar purists might have discouraged this in the past, modern style guides and language experts generally accept starting a sentence with \"so.\"\n\nThere are a few ways \"so\" can be used to begin a sentence:\n\n1. As a transitional word to connect ideas\nExample: \"We discussed the project for hours. So, we decided to take a break.\"\n\n2. To introduce an explanation or conclusion\nExample: \"So, that's why I was late this morning.\"\n\n3. In conversational or informal language\nExample: \"So, how are you doing today?\"\n\nWhile it's acceptable, it's good to use this technique judiciously and be aware of the tone and context of your writing.",
